  [PASS] Data class hierarchy
    Evidence: Dealer extends Player, Player uses Hand, Hand uses Card,
              GameState aggregates all.
    Rank/Suit/GameMode/GamePhase/GameResult/PlayerAction enums are well-
    structured. All model classes implement Serializable with serialVersionUID.
    Inheritance is meaningful: Dealer adds shouldHit() and soft-17 detection.

  [PARTIAL] JavaFX MVC separation
    Evidence: engine/, model/, controller/, view/ packages
    Clean physical separation of concerns: engine holds all business logic,
    model holds data, controller wires engine to UI, view has custom components.
    ISSUE 1: GameController.onHit() directly accesses the deck from the
    controller layer (engine.getGameState().getDeck().drawCard()), which is
    a clear MVC violation — game state manipulation belongs in the engine.
    ISSUE 2: handlePostPlayerTurn() in GameController (GameController.java:340)
    contains game flow decision logic (which phase to trigger) that arguably
    belongs in the engine.
    ISSUE 3: GameController.initMultiplayer() (lines 108-119) is dead code —
    it is never called from any reachable path. MainMenuController routes MP
    to LobbyController → MultiplayerGameController. This dead method creates
    confusion about which controller handles MP.

  [PARTIAL] JavaFX Properties and ObservableList for change notification
    Evidence: GameConfig.java (all fields are IntegerProperty, BooleanProperty,
              StringProperty with proper xxxProperty() accessors)
    Evidence: DealerPlayTask usage in GameController.java:357
              `dealerTask.messageProperty().addListener(...)`
    ISSUE (critical): The main model classes — Player, Hand, GameState — use
    plain int and ArrayList<Card>, NOT JavaFX properties or ObservableList.
    There are ZERO bindings between model state (player chips, hand cards,
    game phase) and the UI labels/card areas. Everything is done via a single
    manual `updateUI()` refresh call after each action.
    GameConfig has proper JavaFX properties but they are NOT bound to the
    Settings UI spinners — SettingsController manually reads/writes values
    with `spnDecks.getValueFactory().setValue(config.getNumberOfDecks())`.
    The only actual property listener is `dealerTask.messageProperty()`, which
    is a Task property, not a model property.
    The spec explicitly requires "napredne i automatizirane mehanizme
    obavještavanja" (advanced automated change notification). This is the
    single largest gap in I1/I2/I3.

  [MISSING] ObservableList used for hand/card binding
