  I4 — Multithreading [~2/14 pts at risk]
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  [PASS] JavaFX Application Thread never blocked
    DealerPlayTask and GameSaveTask both extend javafx.concurrent.Task.
    Their call() methods run on the background pool. Thread.sleep() is only
    inside DealerPlayTask.call() (background thread). GameServer.start()
    blocks but is submitted to AppExecutorService.submit(), not FX thread.

  [PASS] ExecutorService / Task / Service used
    Evidence: AppExecutorService.java — CachedThreadPool + ScheduledExecutorService
    DealerPlayTask extends Task<Void>, GameSaveTask extends Task<Boolean>.
    Both submitted via AppExecutorService.getInstance().submit().
    Graceful shutdown in BlackjackApplication.stop().

  [PASS] Dealer AI async with delays between draws
    Evidence: DealerPlayTask.call() (DealerPlayTask.java:33-77)
    Hole card reveal with delayMs/2 pause. Each card draw followed by
    Thread.sleep(delayMs). updateMessage() updates Task's messageProperty
    which is observed by the FX thread via listener.

  [PASS] Platform.runLater() used correctly
    GameController.handlePostPlayerTurn(): DealerPlayTask callbacks wrapped.
    LobbyController: all network callbacks wrapped.
    MultiplayerGameController: server messages dispatched via runLater.
    ChatPolling: Platform.runLater per batch of new messages.

  [PASS] Chat polling on ScheduledExecutorService
    Evidence: LobbyController.startChatPolling(), MultiplayerGameController.startChatPolling()
    scheduleAtFixedRate() with 500ms interval. New messages batched and
    dispatched to FX thread via Platform.runLater().

  [PARTIAL] Shared state synchronization
    Evidence: DealerPlayTask.call() modifies dealer.getHand() (ArrayList)
    on the background thread. Between `dealer.getHand().addCard(card)` and
    the `Platform.runLater(this::updateUI)` that follows, the FX thread
    could theoretically read the hand list. ArrayList is not thread-safe.
    In practice this is unlikely to cause visible corruption because the
    runLater is posted right after the add, but it is technically an
    unsynchronized concurrent read/write on a non-thread-safe collection.
    GameServer.handleMessage() is correctly synchronized. ClientHandler
    sendMessage() uses synchronized(out). AppExecutorService is synchronized.


