  ================================================================================
  CRITICAL ISSUES (point deductions regardless of category)
  ================================================================================

  1. MISSING ObservableList / Property bindings between model and UI [I1/I2/I3]
     The spec requires "napredne i automatizirane mehanizme obavještavanja"
     (advanced automated change notification). Player, Hand, and GameState
     use plain int and ArrayList — NOT JavaFX properties or ObservableList.
     GameConfig has proper JavaFX properties but they are never bound to UI
     controls — SettingsController manually reads/writes values.
     The only live property listener is `dealerTask.messageProperty()`.
     Everything else uses a manual updateUI() call. This is the pattern
     explicitly NOT required by the spec. Fix: add IntegerProperty to Player
     (chips, currentBet), ObservableList<Card> to Hand, and bind them to
     their corresponding UI Labels.

  2. MISSING JNDI implementation [I6]
     module-info.java declares `requires java.naming` but javax.naming.*
     is never imported or used. RmiServiceManager uses only
     java.rmi.registry.LocateRegistry and Registry. The spec names JNDI
     and RMI as separate requirements. JNDI is completely absent.
     Fix: replace at minimum one LocateRegistry.getRegistry() call with
     an InitialContext lookup using a rmi:// URL, or add a JNDI provider
     lookup for the chat/matchmaking service discovery.

  3. GameController.initMultiplayer() is dead code [I1/I2/I3]
     MainMenuController routes multiplayer to LobbyController, which
     transitions to MultiplayerGameController. GameController.initMultiplayer()
     (lines 108-119) is never called from any reachable code path.
     The method takes a sharedEngine with no card hiding — if it were
     reachable it would expose opponent cards. Not a runtime bug but signals
     incomplete integration between the two multiplayer controllers.

  4. GameController.onHit() bypasses engine for split hand cards [I1/I2/I3]
     Lines 186-190: `engine.getGameState().getDeck().drawCard()` called
     directly in the controller for split hands, bypassing GameEngine.playerHit().
     The engine's turn validation and state management are circumvented.
     This is both an MVC violation and a potential correctness risk.

  5. No Thread.sleep() duration argument — DealerPlayTask constructor only
     Issue is minor but: the delay value (1200ms) is hardcoded at the call
     site in GameController (line 355). This is not configurable via XML.